to the editor history does not support robert a mosbacher 's argument that high oil prices will spur the development of energy alternatives like synthetic fuels renewable energy sources and gasified coal op ed march 13 the two oil shocks in the 1970 's led to the establishment of large government research programs as well as subsidies and tax incentives to encourage development of energy alternatives these programs were mostly a waste of taxpayer money the synthetic fuels program spent millions on hopeless projects ethanol subsidies still remain despite the dim future for ethanol fuels tax incentives encouraged construction of wind turbines but were awarded whether or not the turbines worked when oil prices dropped and stabilized the research programs and tax incentives disappeared we need a sustained effort to encourage alternatives to oil that wo n't happen if government dollars are tied to the fluctuations in oil prices henry wong new haven march 13 2000

